{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509986","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509986"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:22:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:22:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11471"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11471","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11471"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.74,0.13,0.08,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4103"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43723"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4103","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4103"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11471"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28708"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"44"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1498"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"9222"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4965"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6127"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42607"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43231"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43723","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/43723"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 53-year-old woman presents to her General Practitioner with a two-week history of pain in the right side of her face. She describes the pain as a dull ache with unexpected episodes of \u0022electric shocks\u0022 which she feels around her cheek and jaw. She finds that the pain is also triggered by brushing her teeth and chewing. She has tried regular paracetamol (1 g QID) and ibuprofen (200 mg TDS) but these have not provided any relief. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, there is no visible rash and her dentition appears normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most commonly recommended first-line management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increase dose of ibuprofen","Carbamazepine","Baclofen","Phenytoin","Increase dose of paracetamol"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patients likely diagnosis is trigeminal neuralgia. This is evidenced by the characteristic episodic \u0022electric shock\u0022 pain in the distribution of the trigeminal nerve. This pain may be paroxysmal, but may also be triggered by stimuli such as chewing, talking, teething brushing or touching the face.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this patient, the V2 (maxillary) and V3 (mandibular) divisions are affected, which is more common. The V1 (ophthalmic) branch may also be involved, but this is less common. In addition to the episodic \u0022electric shock\u0022 pain, patients also report an underlying ache in the affected region.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of trigeminal neuralgia begins with investigating the cause while providing preventing exacerbations. Investigations may include an MRI of the brain and brainstem to assess for multiple sclerosis and compressive lesions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere are a variety of options to prevent trigeminal neuralgia. However, the quality of the evidence is poor and there are few high-quality randomised controlled trials.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETypically, pharmacotherapy for trigeminal neuralgia requires anticonvulsant medications. Therefore, \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreasing the dose of ibuprofen or paracetamol \u003C/strong\u003Eis unlikely to be effective.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn anticonvulsant such as \u003Cstrong\u003Ecarbamazepine\u003C/strong\u003E is most commonly recommended as first-line for pharmacological management of trigeminal neuralgia.\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003ECarbamazepine should be increased to the maximum tolerated dose before considering other options.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf initial treatment with carbamazepine is insufficient, an additional agent such as lamotrigine, pregabalin or gabapentin may be considered. \u003Cstrong\u003EBaclofen,\u003C/strong\u003E may also be used as an adjunct. Evidence also indicates that baclofen may be useful in those with co-morbid multiple sclerosis as it can assist with spasticity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhenytoin\u003C/strong\u003E is an anticonvulsant, which is used as an infusion at some centres for acute management of severe exacerbations of trigeminal neuralgia. However, there is a lack of evidence for this intervention.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Pharmacotherapy for trigeminal neuralgia is complex and typically requires anticonvulsant medication, most commonly carbamazepine."],"references":["Lambru G, Zakrzewska J, Matharu M. Trigeminal neuralgia: a practical guide. Practical Neurology. 2021;21(5):392-402. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34108244/","Bendtsen L, Zakrzewska JM, Abbott JA, Braschinsky M, Di Stefano G, Donnet A, et al. European Academy of Neurology guideline on trigeminal neuralgia. Eur J Neurol. 2019;26(6):831-49. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30860637/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28708"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11471"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28708","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/28708"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-03-26T13:54:03+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-03-26T13:54:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items",